00:13:07,048 --> 00:13:09,610
They should also be told what some of the risks are,

246
00:13:10,491 --> 00:13:12,572
and if there are any potential benefits involved.

247
00:13:12,933 --> 00:13:14,794
I'll get into this in more detail.

248
00:13:15,795 --> 00:13:18,477
Also, that they're under no obligation to participate,

249
00:13:18,938 --> 00:13:21,039
and again, that they're free to withdraw at any time.

250
00:13:21,640 --> 00:13:24,062
And so it's really in terms of you're being open

251
00:13:24,102 --> 00:13:28,225
and honest about saying, hey, if you're really not into this,

252
00:13:28,706 --> 00:13:30,007
maybe this is not for you.

253
00:13:31,124 --> 00:13:35,568
And I should also know, you know, like what's going to happen, like if you're recording their data,

254
00:13:36,308 --> 00:13:41,332
are you going to identify them in any way? Like if there's a video camera, you know,

255
00:13:41,912 --> 00:13:46,156
are you recording their face, their facial expressions, and is this something that you're

256
00:13:46,176 --> 00:13:50,499
going to keep, or are you going to like maybe gray out or blur out their face or something?

257
00:13:53,910 --> 00:13:56,015
There should be obviously some contact information

258
00:13:56,075 --> 00:13:57,980
so they can ask you later if they have any questions

259
00:13:58,020 --> 00:13:58,682
or concerns.

260
00:13:59,705 --> 00:14:02,371
You should talk about how you're gonna actually use the data.

261
00:14:03,474 --> 00:14:06,915
And so, like, is this something that it's just you who's looking at personally?

262
00:14:07,436 --> 00:14:09,937
Is it a member, you know, is it, like, your team?

263
00:14:10,357 --> 00:14:11,998
Is it everybody from the studio?

264
00:14:12,939 --> 00:14:15,340
Are you going to use it, oh, in a GDC presentation?

265
00:14:15,821 --> 00:14:21,184
You know, and you may not know immediately, like, how far you will take it, but, you know,

266
00:14:21,204 --> 00:14:24,906
you should think about that and say, like, it may be used in these particular spaces.

267
00:14:24,966 --> 00:14:28,928
Maybe you're going to have blog posts or something about, you know, like, testing and what's

268
00:14:28,968 --> 00:14:29,328
going on.

269
00:14:31,041 --> 00:14:34,104
You should have information about any payments or incentives.

270
00:14:34,725 --> 00:14:37,849
And also, you should give them a reasonable amount of time

271
00:14:37,909 --> 00:14:40,311
to go through this so that they don't feel rushed.

272
00:14:40,652 --> 00:14:42,053
And they can also ask questions.

273
00:14:42,974 --> 00:14:45,557
And these things can all be things

274
00:14:45,597 --> 00:14:48,861
that you can either print out so they can read quietly,

275
00:14:49,301 --> 00:14:51,003
or you can explain it to them verbally.

276
00:14:51,363 --> 00:14:51,964
Either way is fine.

277
00:14:55,220 --> 00:14:57,300
Consent also has to be ongoing.

278
00:14:58,180 --> 00:15:00,301
What this means is just that it's not enough

279
00:15:00,401 --> 00:15:02,841
to get somebody to say like, are you okay with this?

280
00:15:02,881 --> 00:15:03,702
I've explained everything.

281
00:15:03,722 --> 00:15:06,162
They're like, yup, and then it's over.

282
00:15:06,782 --> 00:15:09,123
Then you're in prisoner territory.

283
00:15:09,203 --> 00:15:10,943
It's like they said yes once,

284
00:15:11,383 --> 00:15:12,924
and then no matter how horrible it was,

285
00:15:12,944 --> 00:15:14,924
it was like, oh, well, you signed up for it, too bad.

286
00:15:16,964 --> 00:15:19,305
People should feel like they have the opportunity

287
00:15:19,465 --> 00:15:21,045
to leave at any time.

288
00:15:21,485 --> 00:15:25,709
And if, you know, for whatever reason, maybe they don't like the experience, maybe they're

289
00:15:25,729 --> 00:15:26,269
feeling sick.

290
00:15:27,070 --> 00:15:30,512
You know, if they're not having a good time, they're not giving you good data.

291
00:15:31,032 --> 00:15:35,496
And so you need to think about like how, what are the different ways that you could like

292
00:15:36,556 --> 00:15:37,517
remind people.

293
00:15:38,078 --> 00:15:40,820
during the play session, you know, it's okay.

294
00:15:40,840 --> 00:15:42,100
Like, we're gonna take a break now.

295
00:15:42,621 --> 00:15:45,362
If you need to go now, that's cool, whatever.

296
00:15:45,822 --> 00:15:47,784
If you have multiple aspects of the test,

297
00:15:48,164 --> 00:15:49,425
are there things that maybe,

298
00:15:49,705 --> 00:15:51,486
if people are uncomfortable with one aspect,

299
00:15:51,806 --> 00:15:53,567
you know, that you could omit that for them,

300
00:15:54,488 --> 00:15:55,468
but have them do others?

301
00:15:56,009 --> 00:15:58,470
Or maybe you need people to complete the whole experience

302
00:15:58,850 --> 00:16:00,051
and just be up front with people and say,

303
00:16:00,071 --> 00:16:02,412
like, if you're not comfortable with everything,

304
00:16:02,432 --> 00:16:04,213
then this isn't for you.

305
00:16:07,225 --> 00:16:09,870
So again, they should be told that they can stop,

306
00:16:10,250 --> 00:16:11,773
not just leave, but stop at any time.

307
00:16:12,534 --> 00:16:14,157
And the environment should support this.

308
00:16:15,132 --> 00:16:19,214
So it's one thing to say this, and you know, you may not have control over where you're

309
00:16:19,234 --> 00:16:19,994
doing the testing.

310
00:16:20,015 --> 00:16:24,296
You know, maybe it's in a room down a corridor with no windows, and you know, you're sitting

311
00:16:24,317 --> 00:16:24,997
in front of the door.

312
00:16:25,057 --> 00:16:28,158
And I mean, that's like a very, you know, tough thing to do.

313
00:16:28,218 --> 00:16:32,140
Like people are already, as those experiments show, kind of obedient to authority.

314
00:16:32,560 --> 00:16:36,862
Like my students, you know, if I sit at the front of the room and the door is near me,

315
00:16:37,202 --> 00:16:40,424
it's very difficult for them to like get up in the middle of class and walk out, right?

316
00:16:40,464 --> 00:16:41,825
Like that's not a cool thing to do.

317
00:16:42,285 --> 00:16:43,346
They don't want to draw attention.

318
00:16:44,046 --> 00:16:46,248
And that's another way that the environment

319
00:16:46,328 --> 00:16:48,829
can unwittingly shape people's expectations.

320
00:16:49,750 --> 00:16:51,831
So if it's possible for you to think about this

321
00:16:51,911 --> 00:16:54,092
and alter the environment so that people feel comfortable,

322
00:16:54,473 --> 00:16:55,593
that's one thing you can do.

323
00:16:56,374 --> 00:16:58,475
If it's not, then it may be a case

324
00:16:58,515 --> 00:17:00,176
of just reminding people more frequently.

325
00:17:01,016 --> 00:17:02,737
And there should be multiple ways to withdraw.

326
00:17:02,797 --> 00:17:05,799
So maybe they can tell you, or maybe,

327
00:17:06,380 --> 00:17:07,320
like I said, it's a break,

328
00:17:07,380 --> 00:17:08,641
and they just kind of disappear.

329
00:17:12,302 --> 00:17:13,762
So you can use incentives.

330
00:17:16,143 --> 00:17:17,424
You may already use incentives.

331
00:17:18,824 --> 00:17:21,245
Probably for most testing,

332
00:17:21,485 --> 00:17:23,346
and I've found this with testing,

333
00:17:23,646 --> 00:17:27,608
playing the game is often incentive enough for most people.

334
00:17:27,688 --> 00:17:30,869
I ran a study where people were playing games

335
00:17:30,909 --> 00:17:32,010
that had already been released,

336
00:17:32,310 --> 00:17:34,291
the Walking Dead series from

337
00:17:34,971 --> 00:17:37,032
Telltale and also Dragon Age Inquisition.

338
00:17:37,593 --> 00:17:42,396
We asked them to come in for three to six sessions of 90 minutes each,

339
00:17:43,096 --> 00:17:46,718
and we didn't have any dropouts, and we didn't offer any compensation.

340
00:17:46,798 --> 00:17:49,520
They just kept showing up because they enjoyed playing the game.

341
00:17:50,741 --> 00:17:53,802
The one thing to think about in terms of ethics is, you know,

342
00:17:53,923 --> 00:17:56,664
if you're offering very large incentives,

343
00:17:57,165 --> 00:18:01,667
because then it becomes about people just signing up for the money

344
00:18:01,927 --> 00:18:04,549
or whatever the swag is that you're offering them.

345
00:18:07,986 --> 00:18:14,215
So deception, you know, I mentioned you should be up front in telling people what it is that

346
00:18:14,295 --> 00:18:19,283
you're asking them to do, but, you know, is it ever okay to deceive people?

347
00:18:19,783 --> 00:18:21,466
Is it ever ethical to deceive people?

348
00:18:24,071 --> 00:18:25,612
Yes, it can be.

349
00:18:26,172 --> 00:18:27,874
You know, if, as I said,

350
00:18:28,014 --> 00:18:30,215
there are things that you're trying to measure

351
00:18:30,255 --> 00:18:32,477
and if you told people exactly what it was,

352
00:18:33,217 --> 00:18:34,238
you know, that's obviously gonna,

353
00:18:34,878 --> 00:18:36,480
it might change how they react.

354
00:18:37,180 --> 00:18:39,201
But the big thing just to think about is

355
00:18:39,462 --> 00:18:41,963
what's the risk involved in the deception?

356
00:18:42,324 --> 00:18:44,225
And does the benefit of the deception

357
00:18:44,245 --> 00:18:46,286
outweigh any potential risks?

358
00:18:47,068 --> 00:18:50,170
Okay, so this is where you're in the balancing act of,

359
00:18:50,670 --> 00:18:52,071
you know, are you just doing this

360
00:18:52,171 --> 00:18:53,912
because you didn't really think it through,

361
00:18:54,512 --> 00:18:57,614
or, you know, is there like something really important

362
00:18:57,634 --> 00:18:59,314
that you need to get from players,

363
00:18:59,354 --> 00:19:01,335
and if you told them ahead of time, you know,

364
00:19:01,435 --> 00:19:02,136
it would not work.

365
00:19:02,776 --> 00:19:04,437
Also, another thing to keep in mind is,

366
00:19:04,837 --> 00:19:06,378
you know, you've been working with this game,

367
00:19:06,438 --> 00:19:08,999
you're close to it, you know it so intently.

368
00:19:10,360 --> 00:19:12,221
People coming in may have no idea,

369
00:19:12,721 --> 00:19:14,202
really, like, what it is about.

370
00:19:14,710 --> 00:19:18,819
And so for them, many surprises are going to be magnified.

371
00:19:24,876 --> 00:19:26,537
Probably the majority of the time,

372
00:19:28,177 --> 00:19:31,059
the testing that you do under university rules

373
00:19:31,119 --> 00:19:32,859
would qualify as minimal risk.

374
00:19:33,820 --> 00:19:38,142
The university speak for defining minimal risk

375
00:19:38,422 --> 00:19:41,483
is probability and magnitude of possible harms

376
00:19:42,003 --> 00:19:43,624
implied by participation in the study

377
00:19:43,724 --> 00:19:45,945
is no greater than those encountered by participants

378
00:19:46,165 --> 00:19:48,006
in those aspects of their everyday life

379
00:19:48,366 --> 00:19:49,467
that relate to the research.

380
00:19:50,127 --> 00:19:53,948
It's amazing how convoluted universities can make.

381
00:19:54,312 --> 00:19:55,293
You know, simple statements.

382
00:19:55,693 --> 00:19:58,374
So if this is something that people would probably do

383
00:19:58,514 --> 00:20:01,836
in their everyday life, then it's minimal risk, right?

384
00:20:02,116 --> 00:20:05,818
So if your game is rated, you are targeting it like

385
00:20:05,918 --> 00:20:08,019
E for everyone or T for teen, it's probably something

386
00:20:08,039 --> 00:20:09,620
that they would do in their everyday life,

387
00:20:10,201 --> 00:20:12,882
and so you would be qualified as minimal risk.

388
00:20:15,243 --> 00:20:17,605
There are a few times when you go beyond minimal risk.

389
00:20:18,666 --> 00:20:22,649
Minimal risk doesn't mean that you have to ignore all of this, but just that, you know,

390
00:20:22,669 --> 00:20:23,670
the stakes are a little lower.

391
00:20:24,171 --> 00:20:28,314
If you're beyond it, then you do have to think a little bit more carefully, you know, and

392
00:20:28,334 --> 00:20:31,096
you might want to consider some of the resources I suggest at the end.

393
00:20:31,997 --> 00:20:37,201
Beyond minimal risk can happen when suddenly you're involving vulnerable populations, which

394
00:20:37,261 --> 00:20:38,162
is how we talk about them.

395
00:20:38,603 --> 00:20:43,266
So children, those people with diminished capacity, so people with, like, cognitive

396
00:20:43,326 --> 00:20:44,908
impairments, you know, where consent

397
00:20:45,369 --> 00:20:47,570
Maybe something that you have to really think about

398
00:20:47,610 --> 00:20:48,711
how they can understand that.

399
00:20:49,551 --> 00:20:51,033
And also indigenous peoples.

400
00:20:51,433 --> 00:20:55,436
So indigenous peoples in Canada have this very bad history

401
00:20:55,656 --> 00:20:57,317
of being exploited and abused.

402
00:20:57,697 --> 00:20:59,659
They were tested on by different people

403
00:20:59,759 --> 00:21:01,640
just as like a convenient population

404
00:21:01,720 --> 00:21:02,721
to see what would happen.

405
00:21:03,201 --> 00:21:06,263
And so now they get extra protection as a result.

406
00:21:06,984 --> 00:21:09,025
I just wanna talk a little bit more about children though,

407
00:21:09,105 --> 00:21:11,307
cause that's probably the population you would deal with.

408
00:21:12,399 --> 00:21:16,004
So obviously with kids, it's not just the child,

409
00:21:16,084 --> 00:21:18,267
but their parent or their guardian

410
00:21:18,487 --> 00:21:19,589
who would need to consent.

411
00:21:20,530 --> 00:21:23,053
But also think about the age range you're including and why.

412
00:21:23,714 --> 00:21:26,438
Because kids aren't necessarily an amorphous group.

413
00:21:28,219 --> 00:21:33,101
A 7, a 10, and a 13-year-old are all going to be really different in terms of what they

414
00:21:33,141 --> 00:21:38,682
understand, how they think about the world, how they can communicate back to you, what

415
00:21:38,762 --> 00:21:42,424
elements of the game they might think are interesting or exciting or scary.

416
00:21:43,024 --> 00:21:50,666
And so, you know, think carefully about how to, you know, which age ranges you want to

417
00:21:50,706 --> 00:21:51,046
include.

418
00:21:53,427 --> 00:21:53,587
And... .

419
00:21:54,539 --> 00:22:00,481
I would say this is a common recommendation for researching with children.

420
00:22:00,501 --> 00:22:02,922
I would say it would apply to anybody.

421
00:22:03,782 --> 00:22:10,504
As the prior experiments have shown, adults are sometimes uncomfortable with saying, no,

422
00:22:10,564 --> 00:22:11,904
I feel uncomfortable doing this.

423
00:22:12,344 --> 00:22:13,345
Kids are even more so.

424
00:22:13,445 --> 00:22:15,805
So are there ways that with nonverbals you can...

425
00:22:16,225 --> 00:22:18,067
Figure out like they're not having a good time.

426
00:22:18,747 --> 00:22:20,548
You know, are they closed off?

427
00:22:20,768 --> 00:22:22,529
You know, they started laughing, now they're not.

428
00:22:22,549 --> 00:22:24,790
They're looking down, their body language is closed up.

429
00:22:25,151 --> 00:22:27,332
You know, that can be a way that a kid is signaling

430
00:22:27,812 --> 00:22:28,913
they're not comfortable anymore.

431
00:22:30,622 --> 00:22:35,163
I'm not going to talk any more about children, but if you do research or play testing with

432
00:22:35,223 --> 00:22:38,724
kids, I would say check out this talk from The Vault.

433
00:22:39,245 --> 00:22:45,806
In 2014, Gareth Griffiths talked about testing Skylanders with kids of different ages, and

434
00:22:45,846 --> 00:22:48,747
he's got some really good information about how to do that.

435
00:22:56,734 --> 00:23:02,925
So you've identified who you want to test with and what you

436
00:23:02,945 --> 00:23:03,546
want to collect.

437
00:23:04,027 --> 00:23:06,271
Now you want to think about how you're going to store this.

438
00:23:07,393 --> 00:23:08,455
How are you collecting your data?

439
00:23:09,202 --> 00:23:11,122
You know, are you audio, video recording?

440
00:23:11,342 --> 00:23:12,223
Are you going beyond that?

441
00:23:12,263 --> 00:23:13,243
Are you just taking notes?

442
00:23:13,883 --> 00:23:15,043
But how are you storing it?

443
00:23:16,364 --> 00:23:18,625
Is this gonna be secure in any way?

444
00:23:18,645 --> 00:23:22,146
Does every member of the team have access to it?

445
00:23:22,466 --> 00:23:24,326
Which can be fine, but you just need to know

446
00:23:24,386 --> 00:23:25,987
how far you want it to get out.

447
00:23:27,307 --> 00:23:28,948
How are you identifying participants?

448
00:23:29,008 --> 00:23:30,628
You know, are you using their names

449
00:23:30,709 --> 00:23:32,369
or are you taking off their names

450
00:23:32,549 --> 00:23:34,270
and then assigning a pseudonym?

451
00:23:35,334 --> 00:23:36,675
Again, what are you doing with the data?

452
00:23:37,156 --> 00:23:39,539
And also what happens to the data when the study is over,

453
00:23:40,119 --> 00:23:42,142
when your play tests are done, when the game is released?

454
00:23:42,722 --> 00:23:43,844
If you're like me and you're a Packwright,

455
00:23:43,864 --> 00:23:45,306
you tend to just hang on to everything.

456
00:23:45,326 --> 00:23:47,749
You're like, oh, I don't know when I could possibly need this

457
00:23:47,789 --> 00:23:48,509
again, but I might.

458
00:23:49,531 --> 00:23:52,775
But it might be better just to erase it and get rid of it

459
00:23:52,875 --> 00:23:54,917
so that you don't worry about it getting out anywhere.

460
00:23:58,635 --> 00:24:01,237
And related to that, how are you gonna identify these people?

461
00:24:01,257 --> 00:24:04,160
There are different levels of control that you can have.

462
00:24:04,340 --> 00:24:06,682
So you could keep people anonymous.

463
00:24:07,422 --> 00:24:09,244
This usually works with online surveys

464
00:24:09,264 --> 00:24:11,006
where you don't even know who these people are.

465
00:24:11,626 --> 00:24:12,887
But maybe people come through

466
00:24:12,927 --> 00:24:15,209
who never physically identify themselves to you,

467
00:24:15,229 --> 00:24:17,912
and you've got this data that you just,

468
00:24:18,092 --> 00:24:19,613
is literally unlabeled.

469
00:24:20,305 --> 00:24:24,866
More commonly, you know who these people are, and then you have the choice of saying, you

470
00:24:25,006 --> 00:24:28,207
know, we're going to keep this information confidential, like your personal name and,

471
00:24:29,007 --> 00:24:32,568
you know, address, or we're going to identify you.

472
00:24:32,908 --> 00:24:35,909
A lot of times people offer them the choice, like, do you want to be identified or not?

473
00:24:36,349 --> 00:24:39,429
Chances are you're not using this outside of your studio, so it's not going to make

474
00:24:39,469 --> 00:24:39,869
a difference.

475
00:24:40,170 --> 00:24:44,831
But if you did want to use it, you know, in public-facing materials, this is something

476
00:24:44,871 --> 00:24:46,651
like to ask people, are you okay with this?

477
00:24:49,864 --> 00:24:50,445
So VR.

478
00:24:52,966 --> 00:24:58,931
There's a study that came out last year talking about research ethics in VR testing that said,

479
00:24:59,011 --> 00:25:03,775
you know, VR poses risks that are novel, that go beyond the risks of traditional psychological

480
00:25:03,835 --> 00:25:08,198
experiments in isolated environments, and go beyond risks of existing media technology

481
00:25:08,238 --> 00:25:08,958
for the general public.

482
00:25:10,063 --> 00:25:17,125
Even though VR feels pretty new, there have been waves of interest in VR and some researchers

483
00:25:17,165 --> 00:25:18,786
have been studying VR for quite a while.

484
00:25:19,206 --> 00:25:23,647
And so there are a few studies that we can draw on to kind of get a sense of how people

485
00:25:23,687 --> 00:25:27,068
might react with VR systems.

486
00:25:27,088 --> 00:25:29,589
In 2002, there was a study of the virtual pit.

487
00:25:30,502 --> 00:25:33,545
So they had subjects put on a head-mounted display and stand on a ledge.

488
00:25:33,925 --> 00:25:36,507
They were asked to lean over and drop a bean bag into a pit.

489
00:25:36,967 --> 00:25:40,910
Now in reality, they were standing on a wooden platform that was an inch and a half off the

